column168: A passing motorist alerted the driver that there was a problem with his trailer.  The driver stopped and discovered he had product (propionic acid) leaking from the bottom center of the trailer.  The driver proceeded to a nearby parking area off the roadway which he thought would be a safer location to deal with the issue.  He immediately notified Johnsrud Transport of the problem.  At the same time law enforcement officials arrived on scene and notified the local fire department and Oklahoma Highway Patrol.  Sooner Emergency Services, an Oklahoma licensed hazmat response company, was notified and dispatched to the scene.  They diked the area around the trailer to contain the spill and placed containers under the trailer to catch the leaking product while waiting for another trailer to transfer the load to.  Approximately 210 gallons of product was captured in barrels which would leave about 80 gallons that were spilled on the ground.  Sooner Emergency Services cleaned and restored the area to the satisfaction of the Oklahoma Office of Emergency Management which reported the incident to the Oklahoma Dept of Environmental Quality (Incident #74772).  A subsequent internal inspection of the trailer by Stuart Tank, Elkhorn, WI indicated a 5" crack on the curbside of the sump area.

column168: At approx. 0001 on 01/01/2011 the driver arrived at the Southport Mall to deliver a load of propane. The driver ck'd gauge on underground storage tank to verify load would fit. Connected unloading hoses to the riser located approx. 40' from tank. went back to underground storage tank to verify valves were open. Valve area was filled with snow - 3 of the 4 valves were already open - 4th valve was partially open - all piping covered with snow - opened 4th valve rest of way - started truck and proceeded to pump propane into storage tank. Approx. 45 mins later he heard sound of rushing air - ck'd transport for leaks-saw none and looked towards tank area - in the darkness he could see a large vapor cloud - immediately closed all valves on transport and moved emergency valve switch on unloading enclosure to "OFF" position and turned off truck engine. Called 911 - could not get to valves on storage tank due to vapor cloud. It was later determined the valve he opened was an open line with a plastic dust cap attached.(Unable to determine in snow)
column169: All "Dead" valving on storage tanks need to be properly capped or plugged to prevent escape of product should a valve be mistakenly opened. Excess flow valves need to be checked on storage tanks for proper function.

column168: Yardmaster was called by crew passig through yard that a tank car was leaking product from the protctive houseing and that there was ice forming on the top of the car and that an odor can be detcted.  John Vergis, Environmental Officer, was called and when he arrived confirmed the leak and called 911.  When the county HazMat team arrived they set up air monitoring. John Vergis went in with two HazMat team members to investigate the leak.  It was found that liquid was drippig from the housing and ice had formed on the bottom of the housing.  When the housing was opened, ice had consumed the liquid valve on the "B" end of the car.  John Vergis discovered that the valve was not fully tightened and when he cleared the ice away he also found that the plug on the valve was also loose.  The valve was tightened and leak stopped and then the plug was tightened and car was then secure with no further action necessary.
column169: Better loading procedures need to be adopted.

column168: A tanker truck had been loaded with wastewater and was being weighed at the gate of the generator. The driver, making a routine inspection of the  vehicle during that time, noticed a small leak coming from the vent line of the tanker.  A response crew was summoned who donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the leaked material. The clean up material  was placed into a suitable salvage container and taken back into the plant for later shipment.  The cause of the leak was a frozen vent line that did not properly seal. The line was thawed out, re-sealed properly, and the load continued to the intended  waste disposal facility without further incident.    The incident was reported to the State of Minnesota who assigned incident number 116521
column169: Both the driver and the shipper's personnel who were involved with loading the tanker were cautioned to insure that all vent lines are properly closed during sub freezing temperatures

On 1/3/2011 at 22:40 hrs., a car inspector at the CSXT DeWitt yard, East Syracuse, NY, smelled an odor and discovered TCIX 210123, a loaded tank car of Corrosive Liquids, Toxic, N.O.S., dripping from the B-End stub sill area of the car. The car was isolated and notifications were made to CHEMTREC #2011-0103-00168, NYS-DEC #1010330, NRC #963641, and the shipper's representative, Bruce McElheny, 225-293-8266 ext 14. EP+S of Vermont, a CSXT emergency repsonse contractor, was dispatched to the scene and determined the tank car was leaking product at the B-end stub sill. The consignee, TDC (CSX Transflo Terminal) was advised to off load TCIX 210123 into truck tank trailers and request an FRA movement approval returing the car to home shop for repairs.    This incident did require a special shipping move.  An AAR QA Program 7.1 Nonconformance Report was completed for this incident.    Cause Code: 662  NARRI: 2 (5+5+1) x (2+0) = 44
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 01/06/2011 at 11:16 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Rocky Mount yard in Rocky Mount, NC, discovered FURX 120317, a loaded tank car of Isopropyl Acetate, leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, HCH Marketing, was contacted via CHEMTREC, Report 2011-01-06-00072. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to the bottom outlet valve operating handle pinned and secured with a seal in the open position and the bottom outlet cap less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative, Sue Schwartz at 281-331-7766 ext. 104. HEPACO personnel placed the bottom outlet valve operating handle in the closed position and tightened the secondary securement cap with a wrench. The leak was secured and the car was released to destination.    This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause code: 148  NARRI: 5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80
column169: Review proper securement procedures with operators.

column168: When making a yard inspection I found that this car had oil residue on the side of the it.  It was evident that it was a fresh leak.  I climbed the car to investigate to fids that the oil was coming from under the bread box cover.  I opened the cover to find that the liquid valve was not attached to the car.  The valve had a threaded connection.  The valve was laying on top the tank still attached by a chain to the car.  I reinstalled the valve using thread sealant.  I called Chemtrec to notify the shipper and when the shipper called I asked that they come out and wipe the oil residue off the side of the car.

column168: Transport was traveling southbound on hwy 85. The unit crossed the grass median and the northbound lanes and crashed on the east shoulder of the hwy. The tractor and trailer separated. The tractor came to rest in an irrigation canal upside down. The driver was laying in water and was pinned in the wreckage of the truck. The trailer came forward and struck the cab of the tractor and then came to rest on the right side of the unit. The trailer began leaking liquid at the vapor line piping on the bottom of the transport tank. The driver had to be extricated from the wreckage by the fire department. The driver was alert and conscious but had extensive injuries. The driver was transported by medical helicopter to Denver Health Hospital in Lakewood, CO. Hazmat teams and fire department units assisted with vapor control and the product was transfered from transport to transport. Both units were removed from the scene and have been secured as of the time of this report. Hazwoper clean up crews are currently working to remediate vehicle fluids which were spilled in the canal.
column169: Accident is under investigation at this time.

column168: The cause of the spill was due to improper preparation for transportation.  The shipper shrink wrapped the skid to a drum for transport.  During transit the drum broke the skid and fell through.  This resulted in the skid puncturing the bottom of the drum, with a hole the size of a pin hole.. column168: ON 01/10/11 AT APPROXIMATELY 1251 A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN THE SRC QC AREA OF THE DHL EXPRESS SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT 236 WENDELL H FORD BLVD, ERLANGER, KY 41018. INSPECTION OF THE SHIPMENT PRESENTED A SUITCASE CONTAINING NUMEROUS ITEMS INCLUDING NON REGULATED WINE WHICH HAD BROKEN AND CAUSED THE LEAK. THE FOLLOWING REGULATED ITEMS WERE FOUND WITHIN THE SUITCASE:1(6.8 OZ) METAL BOTTLE GARNIER MOUSE-CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE, 2 (0.5 OZ)GLASS BOTTLES OPI NAIL LAQUER-FLAMMABLE, 1 (100 ML)GLASS BOTTLE ACQUA DI COLONIA-POSSIBLE FLAMMABLE, 1 (7 ML)GLASS BOTTLE ROUGE RAISER PARIS-LAQUE EVIDEMMENT-POSSIBLE FLAMMABLE, 1 (8.5 ML) GLASS BOTTLE DEBORAH SHINE TECH-POSSIBLE FLAMMABLE, 2 (0.16 OZ) GLASS BOTTLES SEPHORA-POSSIBLE FLAMMABLE, 3 (0.5 OZ) GLASS BOTTLES ESSIE-POSSIBLE FLAMMABLE, 1 (3.4 OZ) GLASS BOTTLES EAU DU LIT-POSSIBLE FLAMMABLE, 4 (0.04 OZ) GLASS BOTTLES CHLOE-POSSIBLE FLAMMABLE, 1 (1 OZ)GLASS BOTTLE JO MALONE-POSSIBLE FLAMMABLE. NONE OF THESE ITEMS LEAKED. THIS WAS A 2 PIECE SHIPMENT, BOTH PIECES WERE LUGGAGE WEIGHING APPROXIMATELY 74 KG EACH. THE SECOND PIECE WAS LOCATED AT THE JFK DHL FACILITY. THE INNER CONTENTS OF THIS PIECE CONSISTED OF SEVERAL NON REGULATED PERSONAL ITEMS AND ONE BOTTLE OF POTENTIALLY REGULATED HAND SANITIZER. TRACKING INDICATES INITIAL TRANSPORTATION BY AIR.

column168: Jess Wyatt DSR from XKC was unloading this trlr. He had unloaded one Haz Mat shipment and there was no damage.  He commented that he smelled paint but couldn't see anything leaking.  The front half of the trlr was loaded by LOO and was left on the trlr at XWK and more freight was added to it.  Several employee's smelled the paint but no one could see any problem.  When Mark Jones DSR went out to hook to the trlr, he found blue paint running out from under the trlr.  Trlr was then unloaded at the XWK dock and we found that the frt that was floor loaded behind the paint had been shoved through the plywood sheet that was there to protect it and had punctured or broken the bottom seal on the can allowing it to leak on to the floor and run out the bottom of the trlr.  Floor dry was used to clean up the spill both in the trlr and on the ground. The damaged drum was put into a salvage drum awaiting further disposition.

column168: While travelling on Interstate 30 eastbound, near mile marker 20, the driver of the tractor-tanker unit lost control of the vehicle, due to slippery road conditions.  An initial investigation of the accident was completed and it was determined that there was no release of any free product.  Due to slippery road conditions on Interstate 30, a large stretch of the Interstate was shut down by local authorities.  On January 11, 2010, the Bayer Material Science emergency response unit began the product transfer.  The product was loaded into a new tanker provided by Slay Transportation Co., Inc.  The Bayer Material Science emergency response unit confirmed that there was no release of any product from the overturned tanker.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and may have been related to slippery road conditions, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Responders found leak (odor/smell) originating from DOWX 72241.  The Louisiana State Police, Steve Childers, was on site for response and identified this car. These release was not liquid material, but was vapor-odor emitting from defective closure. Leak found to originate from a loose four bolt flange below the liquid line valve connecting to the dip tube. The four bolts were found finger tight. The responders tightened this flanged fitting tool tight correcting the release. Appears when Exxonmobil unloaded this car, they connected to the four bolt flange located below the valve and failed to tighted it when finished.  Chemtrec was notified by KCS CID, who in turn notifed Exxonmobil. No Chemtrec call back was received from shipper Exxonmobil responding to this incident.  Mr. Mike Accettella, Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality, 318-308-1770, called requesting a verbal report which was provided.     KCS emergency mitigation services were activated to provide for special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, dedicated internal management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory reporting as appropriate.  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply as services require.    Report Notes:  Item 13; No consignee information was provided on the waybill. The UP Railroad is shown on waybill to delivery switch car to consignee at Bayport, TX. The consignee information is unknown by KCS. Exxonmobil or UP can provide this data.     Item 19: No liquid product was released by this car. Only product odor vapors were release. PHMSA DOT reporting system defects will not allow reporting release in units other than what is used for reporting capcity. Therefore this vapor odor release was reported as 0.1 gallon to make the PHMSA DOT system accept report.     Item 27, amount in package, was estimated by preparer. This action was to facilitate data acceptance by defective PHMSA DOT IT system edits. Specifically, this estimated quantity was required for two reasons:   (1)because the shipper only provided bulk quantity on shipping paper, as 1 Tank Car, per PHMSA DOT requirements; and   (2)because the PHMSA DOT e-system requires data in this field which use the same units of measure as found in the capacity field.   KCS will continue to report in this fashion unit instructed differently by DOT or PHMSA.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  Also, please reference http://nar.aar.com/ for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: While inspecting train for odor report, found a tank car, UTLX 203440, load Diisopropyl Ether, Class 3. Responder found two emissions from this car. One at the liquid line valve where valve thread connection is made to tank car. And a second at the threaded connection of the vacuum relief valve where valve threads to manway cover. Responder tightened the liquid valve  turn correcting the small leak. However, the responder tried to tighten the vacuum relief valve connection but couldnt tighten enough to correct leak. The tank car does have a nitrogen pad.  The shipper Exxonmobil was notified via Chemtrec and responded to the site replacing the vacuum vent valve. The new valve threads were prepared with teflon tape sealant when reapply correcting the release point.  A 4 PSI Nitrogen pad was re-applied to this car and a field leak test was completed and passed. This car now requires a formal leak test by a qualified provider or a FRA One Time Movement Approval before it can proceed in transportation.  Shipper Exxonmobil is working on securing either movement approval or leak test for this car. Louisiana state police was notified at 2:45pm, report number 11-00272. Chemtrec re-notify at 3:05pm, under same report number.     KCS emergency mitigation services were activated to provide for special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, dedicated internal management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory reporting as appropriate. column168: Driver arrived at destination, began offloading product. Product began to vent from vent stack at rear of trailer. Driver closed discharge valve and shut down offloading procedure. Driver disconnected delivery hose and moved trailer away from loading dock to a safe location.  Driver determined the cause of product venting was from a failed rupture disc. The rupture disc is flange mounted and is located at the rear of the trailer in the secondary pressure relief system piping.  Duration of product release was approximately five hours.   A replacement disc was delivered to the site, an engineer was called to the location, failed rupture disc was replaced, abating the release of product.
Shipment was found damaged while on our dock. We are unable to determine who or what caused the spill.

column168: During normal switching operations PTRA train crew observed product dripping from the bottom outlet valve cap on UTLX 46892 at approximately 1119 AM on January 21, 2011. They immediately notified the Yardmaster on duty and left the area until the car could be inspected.  Shipper (Southern Chemical/ITC) were notified of the incidnet and they sent a response team to the scene. Ruben Romero from Union Tank Car and Cory Guccione from ITC arrived on scene at 1220 PM along with PTRA Director of Safety and Environmental.  It was determined that the bottom outlet handle was loose and the valve itself was defective allowing product to bypass the valve and collect in the cap.  There were two gaskets inside the cap and product was able to bypass the gaskets and leak around the cap threads. Absorbent pads were inserted into the pipe below the valve, a new gasket was installed and the cap was replaced. The car is currently being held pending an FRA MA to move the car back into ITC to be unloaded and have the valve replaced. The leak was stopped and car secured at 1250 PM.
column169: ITC is investigating the cause of the valve failure and will advise handling.

column168: A BNSF roll-by inspection of a BNSF unit train standing on the main track within the railyard revealed entrained UTLX 209040 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from its bottom outlet valve (BOV). The Willmar Fire Department was notified and responded. The FD responders reported that the bottom outlet valve's operating handle was in the open position and not secured or pinned which allowed product to leak out at the bottom outlet's closure cap (BOC) which was hand tight. The FD closed the BOV which ended any further product release by 1240 hrs. CST, 1/05/2011. Afterwards, BNSF contract responders arrived and checked securement of UTLX 209040. These responders tool tightened the BOC on UTLX 209040 and inspected the remainder of the train's entrained railcars for securement issues. The responders reported finding four other tank cars in the train with the BOV's in the closed position, but the BOC's were less than tool tight. Three of these showing indications of product wetness around the BOC's threaded connection. These BOC's were tool tightened.  Product that impacted ground covering snow was shoveled into recovery drums. Pooled spillage atop the frozen ground was absorbed with pad material.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: An inbound BNSF train inspection in the railyard revealed PROX 31819 (DOT 112J340W tank car) emanating a slight product odor.  BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected PROX 31819 and reported that the odor was emanating from the valve housing area. Valve inspection revealed the B-end liquid valve was not in the fully closed position and it appeared that product by-passed this valve's closure plug that was heavily taped, but tool tight. After the liquid valve was closed the odor dissipated. No further product release was evident after additional leak testing conducted.  Response was concluded by 1800 hrs. CST, 1/13/2011. Intact valve housing seal was replaced by BNSF seal numbered 002462.   The shipper was contacted and after unloading, PROX 31819 will be directed to a qualified repair facility for valve inspection.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: ON 01/13/11 AT APPROXIMATELY 0924,ROBERT ST GEORGE OF THE DHL MIA GATEWAY LOCATED AT 5975 North West 18th, MIAMI, FLORIDA 33126 CALLED THE DHL EXPRESS DANGEROUS GOODS HOTLINE TO ADVISE OF AN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. ROBERT ADVISED THAT DURING A CUSTOMS INSPECTION OF SHIPMENT 2362827331, 20 VIALS MARKED DRAGER ROHRCHEN HYDROGEN SULFIDE (UN1053) WERE FOUND ALONG WITH SEVERAL NON REGULATED ITEMS INSIDE THE SHIPMENT. TRACKING INDICATES INITIAL TRANSPORTATION BY AIR.

The freight forwarder " AIR-SEA" tendered a shipment of "consol,battery-module"   for a passenger flight. The shipper had indicated in writing that the shipment was " not hazardous" .The forwarder had no other information until they were entering the US census information in a computer, then the forwarder noticed that the word " lithium" was used to describe the battery module in the computer data or program. The forwarder notified the airline.   The shipment had been loaded on ULD at the cargo area of the airline but not yet transported to the passenger ramp area.   The airline stopped and held the shipment and notified the FAA.   Once the FAA was done the shipment was released to the forwarder with the instructions not to transport the shipment by air.

column168: GATX 10991 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard was reported dripping liquid from the bottom of this tank car. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected GATX 10991 and reported that the drip source was at the bolted blind flange closure at the bottom washout appurtenance located where the bottom outlet would be positioned. Two of the four flange mounting bolts or stud nuts were less than tool tight by 1/8 to 1/4 turn. These flange bolts/nuts were tool tightened ending further droplets. The droplets that fell landed on a rail crosstie and did not impact the ground soil.

THE SPILL LASTED FOR 30 MINUTES AND 142 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS CAPTIVATED INSIDE THE TERMINALS SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SYSTEM AND PIPED TO A TANK.

AMCX 29183 was observed leaking by the PTRA Manchester Yard Carman at approximately 2030 hrs on Thursday, January 27, 2011. PTRA Trainmaster Young responded to the scene and contacted M&M Protection at INEOS' request to respond the the leak. M&M arrived on scene and determined that product was leaking from the connection between the 3" to 2" reducer and the valve/nipple assembly on the liquied line. They were able to tighten the valve assembly and nipple by approximately a three quarter turn stopping the leak. There was teflon tape on the threads however it appears it came off of the threads as the nipple/valve assembly was tightened onto the reducer allowing product to leak around the threads. Total product leaked was approximately one gallon with some product on the cross ties beneath the car.  M&M cleaned up all product on the ground and washed down the car and ground with a water/microbug solution. The car was secured and the scene was cleared at 0115 hrs on January 28.
column169: INEOS has launched an internal ivestigation into the cause of the leak. It has been reported that this is the second load the car has had since it was requalified in 2009. The car sat in storage for some time before being returned to service.

column168: A 345 gallon IBC was transported from the generator's location to the Veolia ES Technical Solutions ten-day intransit facility located in Blaine, MN. Once at the ten-day location the IBC was reloaded onto a van trailer. The next day as additional containers were being added to the van, a small leak was observed coming from the IBC. The contents of the IBC were then transferred to another IBC and the spill cleaned up. Further investigation revealed that the weld seam next to one of the legs of the IBC was cracked and was the source of the leak.
column169: While this type of leak from a small crack in the weld on the bottom of the IBC is very difficult to detect, we have reviewed this incident with the field personnel. In addition we have emphasized the need to diligently inspect all containers prior to shipment to ensure they are in good condition.

column168: January 31, 2011: While performing a routine inspection at Conrail's Burlington, NJ yard, FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector R. Mr. Dedow notified CR's A. Richter, Risk Manager of the release by phone.      Later response and inspection by Mr. Richter and REACT Environmental (emergency response contrator for Conrail) R. Gould, found the manway cover gasket with an approximate 2 1/2" piece of gasket missing.  The overall condition of the remainder of the gasket was deteriorated.    Gasket removed, replaced with an EPDM manway nozzle gasket.  Manway cover closed, resecured and car okayed for forwarding to original destination. column168: GATX 44258 was reported to be releasing product from the top of the tank car in the Neff Yard; Kansas City, MO.  Inspection of the car found no rupture disk in the Salco Quick Inspect Safety Vent housing and the rupture disk holder itself was laying on top of the car.  Further inspection found the thread collar on the Quick Inspect Body to have been broken off, allowing the rupture disk and holder to come out of the Quick Inspect body, releasing approximately 10 gallons of product to the tank car with none reaching the ground.         Haz-Mat Response (Contractor) responded and decontaminated the car with a water/citric acid solution.  The car was temporarily secured by installing a new frangible disk and replacing the disk holder.  The disk holder was retained by two bungee cords and the entire assembly was then bagged with a  plastic bag.       On 1/21/11, representative of Occidental Chemical (Shipper) responded, replaced the Salco housing and requalified the tank car.  The car was then released to continue in transportation.

column168: This was a three vehicle accident. A car merged onto the freeway erratically in front of another 18 wheeler (cowtown redimix) which was traveling in the second lane to the right on a four lane highway. The driver of the redimix truck made an unsafe lane change into our tanker truck which was in the second lane. The impact caused our tanker truck to loose control and hit the center barrier and roll over on its driver side. The driver and passenger or the driver of the redimix truck never came into contact with the fuel released from our tanker truck. Our driver had minor injuries from the accident but not from the material released.The Dallas FD chose to let the release burn off rather than spray it with water. The release after the fire was put out was minimal and was contained in the storm sewer and creek with containment boom. The release was reported to NRC and TCEQ and a Haz-Mat crew was dispatched as soon as we were notified of the accident. TCEQ and the city of Dallas had representatives on site to assure the response and remediation was taken care of. The truck was carrying 6835 Unleaded, 1010 Premium Unleaded, and 949 Diesel Fuel

column168: On the morning of January 4, 2011 at approximately 0915 our driver reported that he had a damaged 275 gallon IBC of Sulfuric Acid 93%.  He stated that he had been moving it to the rear of our delivery trailer with a powered pallet jack and the throttle stuck.  He used the kill switch as the front of the pallet jack was off the rear of the trailer and the IBC had fallen off the back of the trailer.  When it hit the ground, it ruptured the bottom of the IBC leaking 2/3 of its contents.  The forklift operator of our customer lifted the IBC and placed it into a containment area, which collected in their wastewater system.  We then called IMS Environmental Services and notified them of the incident and requested a response team to assist.  While enroute to the incident, at approximately 1020, I called the NRC.  IMS arrived onscene and began pumping the material into another IBC.  Once all of the material was pumped, we began neutralizing the area and then powered washed it into a sump collection on the customer's site which would be processed in their wastewater system.
column169: Industrial Chemicals is investigating the cause of the throttle sticking and also implementing a safety barrier as the driver brings items to the rear of trailers.

column168: On January 10, 2011, Veolia employees in Schenectady, NY discovered a leaking 55-Gallon drum while unloading a vehicle at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY transfer facility. Approximately three gallons of material leaked onto the floor of the commercial motor vehicle. It was determined that the container leaked because the lid of the drum popped open after the ring securing it failed. It is assumed that the ring failed when the drum bumped against another drum druing transport. The container was checked and resealed and checked again for a properly fitting closure ring and cover. The container was then shipped to the disposal facility originally destined. The material that leaked was cleaned up and sent to a proper waste disposal facility. The container information is as follows: 1A2/Y1.2/100/USA/MS660?10/RL. The container was purchased from Tricorbraun and was manufactured by American Container.
column169: Veolia employees at GE, Aviation in Lynn were retrained to make sure lids are properly attached using the closure instructions. Veolia employees have also asked GE to consider using new drums instead of reconditioned drums for hazardous materials shipments.

column168: During off loading of dilute ammonium hydroxide solution the transfer hose developed a pinhole leak. The transfer was immediatley stopped by the driver by shutting off the air supply to the tanker. Less than five gallons of dilute ammonium hydroxide was released into a concrete containment unloading area. An emergency response contractor was engaged to clean up the release.
column169: The chemical transfer hose utilzed for the transfer is a Fabcem hose manufactured by Goodyear which is compatible for use with ammonium hydroxide solution.  Chemical transfer hoses are pressure tested and visually inspected annually. The hoses are also inspected monthly , and daily prior to use. Preventative maintenance inspection and testing records of the hose were reviewed. The subject hose was pressure tested and visually inspected in June , 2010. The unloading hose was examined for signs of wear and tear. There were no obvious abrasions, cuts or evidence of wear and tear on the exterior of the hose.     The facility is evaluating the inspection frequency and service life for chemical transfer hoses. The incident was discussed at the facility safety meeting with all applicable employees.

column168: (A&B)On 01/06/2011 at 18:30pm EST, CN train L50261-06 derailed 12 cars at Durand, Michigan. Local emergency services and CN's hazmat contractor responded to the scene, two tank cars were noted leaking due to the derailment. GATX 60995 (L/ Hydrochloric Acid) derailed on its side and was leaking approximately one drop per minute from the pressure plate and GATX 61247 (L/ Hydrochloric Acid) derailed upright all wheels off the track and was leaking approximately 10 gallons per minute due to a dent/puncture on the tank shell head, B end of car. Local emergency services decided to evacuate near-by homes as a precaution, no injuries were reported. Evacuation was lifted once product transfers were complete.     GATX 60995 Class: 8 UN1789 - L (Hydrochloric acid)  Uprighted and product transferred  into trucks on site. Approximately 10 gallons of product lost. Car to be destroyed.    GATX 61247 Class: 8 UN1789 - L (Hydrochloric acid) CN response contractor was able to pull a vacuum on the car stopping the leak, a wax/ring patch was then applied. Product  transferred into trucks on site. Approximately 937 gallons of product lost. Car to be destroyed.
column169: No additional comments.

It was found one wet battery inside a fiberboard box in a courier bag. The courier bag didn’t have any kinds of dangerous goods markings or labels at all. Indeed, it was detected because the flight coordinator noticed the courier bag was wet, and an unknown liquid was spilled all over the floor. Immediately, a security officer and the flight coordinator proceeded to open the bag, thus it was found that the fiberboard box was broken and the battery was head down spilling all the liquid inside, which it seemed to be acid because of its reaction with floor and its repulsive odor. Right away, a dangerous goods agent was contacted, who take care of the spilled, and set a hold status to the awb. In addition, the nature of the awb is courier.

column168: A set of refurbished triple seats was delivered to our Stores facility from the vendor. The life vests were installed underneath the seats. The package that the seats arrived in were never opened thus, our Stores location had no idea that these life vests were installed underneath the seats. When the set of seats needed to be shipped to PHX, our MOW Stores labeled the seats for PHX and shipped them. Again, not knowing that the life vests were installed as they were still in the original packaging from the vendor and had never been opened. When the set of seats arrived in PHX, the seats were opened to be prepared for installation. That's when they noticed that the life vests were installed. MOW Stores did not knowingly offer these for shipment.
column169: 1. An immediate inventory was taken and all of our seats were checked for any life vests installed.2. Our computer system was updated to advise all Stock Clerks to check for any life vests installed before shipping these seats.3. Communication was sent out to all Stores locations and Stock Clerks advising of the shipment and the preventative measures put in place.

HE AT ONCE FOUND THE LEAKING DRUM AND WEARING THE APPROPRIATE PPE (PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT) HE TURNED THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE SO THE PUNCTURED AREA WAS ABOVE THE LIQUID. A POLICE CAR PULLED UP AND NOTIFIED THE BASE FIRE DEPARTMENT WHO CLOSED THE GATE TO INCOMING TRAFFIC. THE BASE FIRE DEPT ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 0815 AND AFTER TALKING TO THE DRIVER AND OUR PLANT MANAGER BY PHONE THEY RE-OPENED THE GATE TO TRAFFIC.  THE FIRE DEPT HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED ABOUT 0900 AND PROCEEDED TO PUT SALT ON THE SPILL WHICH WAS JUST AROUND THE TRAILER. THE FIRE DEPT HAZMAT TEAM FINISHED ABOUT 0920.  ALLIED UNIVERSAL SENT 2 RESPONDERS WITH AN OVERPACK DRUM AND SODIUM BICARB TO CLEAN UP AND NEUTRALIZE THE AREA.  CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED ABOUT 1130 AND ALL MATERIALS WERE TAKEN BACK TO THE ALLIED BRUNSWICK PLANT FOR REUSE.

column168: A Dakota Southern Railway Co. crew reported to BNSF that ATSF 524938 (AAR R410 boxcar) was emanating an odor in the railyard. BNSF contract responders inspected ATSF 524938 finding small amounts of commodity has sifted through gaps between the boxcar door and door frame. The escaping commodity contacted melting snow, reacting and off-gassing an ammonia odor. The responders applied expanding foam sealant at the boxcar doorway gaps to prevent any further commodity seepage. The interior conditions inside ATSF 524938 were not inspected. Afterwards, no further odor was present or vapors detectable using air monitoring devices. ATSF 524938 was redirected back to the origin shipper for their evaluation and necessary adjustments.

column168: 911 was called by the driver immediately. Sooner Emergency Response Services, Inc. was contacted to perform remediation cleanup services.    Tractor/trailer had jackknifed after colliding with another vehicle while traveling north bound on a snow and ice packed roadway. The tractor/trailer slid into the center median and was leaking fuel. Sooner Emergency Service was requested to conduct an emergency response to the site and perform remediation cleanup services as required. Appropriate technicians and equipment were immediately dispatched to the site to perform the operations.    Technicians arriving on site found a Dynamex Operations East, Inc tractor/trailer  had slid into the center median and struck the DOT cable barrier. The barrier  performed as expected and prevented the tractor/trailer from entering the south  bound lane. The left fuel tank was ruptured by the jack down dolly on the trailer  and the center median barrier cable ruptured the right fuel tank.    A traffic directional arrow board and reflective traffic cones were set in place to  designate the area a work zone and aleli the motoring public of the situation as  they approached the site. The tractor/trailer was against the cable barrier and had  stretched the cable to a point that the truck could not be moved.    As the tractor/trailer set in the median against the cable barrier, fuel continued to slowly leak from the left fuel tank. This leaking could not be stopped until the  wrecker service could move the tractor from the site. The right fuel tank that was  ruptured by the bal1'ier cable had lost an unknown amount of fuel prior to technicians arriving on site. The cable had cut into the tank and was temporarily  mended to prevent fuliher leakage. The cable barrier system was not broken but  was entangled in and under the tractor and trailer. The system can only be  removed by qualified DOT personnel, who were notified. DOT personnel advised  that due to weather conditions, personnel would arrival on site on the following  day to perform the procedures which will allow the tractor/trailer to be freed from  the entanglement.    The leaking fuel was leaking onto a three foot wide concrete drainage slab in the  center median and migrating to the north. The fuel migrated along the slab for a  distance of 175 feet before entering a drop box and then into a shaft leading to an  underground stonn water runoff tunnel. The fuel dumped into a drainage tunnel  that was 6 feet by 6 feet in size and lUns from east to west under the roadway.  Technicians entered the tunnel and set absorbent booms, hydrocarbon absorbent  pads, and bio matrix in the tunnel to contain the fuel.    Absorbent booms were set in place along the drainage slab to contain the fuel as it  leaked fi·om the tractor's tanks. A micro blaze emulsifier was placed in the drop  box to eradicate and break down the filel that had entered the box and the drainage  tunnel. Bio matrix absorbent, safe step absorbent, and absorbent

column168: UTLX 208140 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking product from a top fitting area during normal rail movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 208140. The responder reported product wetness on one side of the tank shell that traced back to the 165 psi pressure relief valve/device (PRV/PRD) mounted atop UTLX 208140. Further inspection of the PRV/PRD revealed that the top stem cover and cover screw were missing which allowed the stem and stem washers to move freely with subsequent product expulsion from this orifice during rail movement. UTLX 208140 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting the application of a new replacement PRV/PRD. Spillage on UTLX 208140's side shell evaporated and no ground impact from spillage was observed. The shipper was notified and a suitable replacement PRV/PRD was procured for installation upon UTLX 208140.  As of 2/09/2011, the replacement PRV/PRD has been shipped but not yet received for installation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 1/25/2011 at approx. 23:41 hrs., personnel in the CSXT South Philadelphia yard discovered ACFX 72480, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Westway Terminal Company, local, state and federal agencies as applicable were notified via CHEMTEL Report 13232. React Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that 8 of 8 manway bolts were less than tool tight and the manway cover gasket was down inside the car. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Criag Pataky 215-425-3707. React Environmental personnel applied a manway cover gasket and secured the manway cover bolts tool tight and the car was released for transport.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 207  NARRI: 5 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: On 01/26/2011 at approx. 14:00 hrs., CSXT notified the shipper, BP Canada Energy Marketing, that GATX 78102, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Gases, Liquified, was overweight at the CSXT South Philadelphia yard. The shipper contacted emergency response contractors, Specialized Professional Services Inc (SPSI) to inspect the car. As SPSI personnel was unscrewing the gauging device cap, product was released. SPSI personnel discovered a leaking magnetic gauging device. The gauging device cap was reapplied and the leak was contained. The tank car was transferred into tank trucks and the car was flared off to remove remaining vapors. The issue was identified and the corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, John Gustafson 630-420-4446. The car will be home shopped for repair.     This incident did require a special switching move.   This incident will require a 7.1 QA Non conformance report.    Cause Code: 481  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: On 01/29/2011 at 03:15 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Selkirk yard in Selkirk, NY discovered UTLX 76344, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquids, N.O.S., with product on the sides of the tank car and a heavy odor in the air. The car was isolated and CHEMTREC was notified report 2011-01-29-00017, requesting contact with the shipper, NYS-DEC were notified report #1011015. EP+S of Vermont, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway swing bolts were less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Steve Hamilton 770-570-1601. EP+S of Vermont inspected the manway gasket and re-secured the manway cover and swing bolts. The spill area on the car was  wiped down, security seals applied and the car was inspected for further leaks. Finding none, the car was released for transportation.    This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 01/31/2011 at 11:27 hrs., personnel at the Wauhatchie yard in Chattanooga, TN, discovered GATX 200771, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking liquid from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated in the rail yard away from CSXT employees and the shipper, Poet Biorefining, was notified. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found two bolts on the manway cover were less than tool tight and the manway gasket was found to have cracks and signs of deterioration. HEPACO tightened the bolts and replaced the car manway gasket stopping the leak. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Ben Sweat, Poet Ethanol products, 1-316-303-1385. The car was then released for transportation to destination.    This incident did not require a special switching move.   A QA 7.1 is required for this incident.    Cause Code: 209  NARRI: 5 (3+3+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: WHILE SORTING PACKAGES IN THE WILLOW GROVE UPS HUB, EMPLOYEES NOTICED SMOKE FROM A PACKAGE THAT HAD BEEN CAUGHT IN A JAM ON THE CONVEYOR BELT AND WAS SUBSEQUENTLY DESCENDING A METAL CHUTE.  THE EMPLOYEES IMMEDIATELY SUMMONED HELP FROM OTHERS IN THE FACILITY.  THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED BY EMPLOYEES USING HAND-HELD FIRE EXTINGUISHERS.  IN THE REMNANTS WERE 10 AEROSOLS FROM A PACKAGE THAT APPEARED TO BE THE SOURCE, BUT WHICH HAD BURNED TOO MUCH FOR ITS ORIGIN, DESTINATION AND TRACKING NUMBER TO BE IDENTIFIED.  FROM THE REMNANTS, IT APPEARS THAT THE VALVE OF AT LEAST ONE AEROSOL RELEASED ITS CONTENTS, CAUSING A FLAMMABLE MIXTURE THAT WAS IGNITED BY STATIC ELECTRICITY.  TWO AEORSOLS IN THIS PACKAGE HAD LOST THE BOTTOM HEADS, PROBABLY DUE TO FIRE DAMAGE.  THERE WAS A VERY BRIEF DISRUPTION OF THE WORK IN THE AREA OF THE FIRE BUT NO INJURY OR FACILITY DAMAGE.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, a third party struck the McKinley Trucking Co., Inc. vehicle, which damaged the load-head and caused a release from the load pipe on the tanker.  Michigan State Police responded to assess the site.  Sunpro, Inc. was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, free product was detected on the roadway.  Approximately 5 gallons of gasoline had released from the load pipe to the asphalt surface.  Sunpro, Inc. utilized absorbents to recover the free product, which were containerized into one (1) 55-gallon recovery drum, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There was no impact to soil or waters of the state as a result of the incident.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a third party striking the McKinley Trucking Co., Inc. vehicle, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  McKinley Trucking Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, trailer broke-free of tractor, which caused trailer to roll onto its side on Interstate 70.  Colorado Highway Patrol and Local Fire Department responded to the site.  I-70 was shutdown as a result of the incident. Regulatory agencies were notified and Custom Environmental Services of Arvada, Colorado was dispatched to the site for cleanup.  A containment pool was placed beneath the leaking tanker to secure the release, pending response contractor and offload.  Upon arrival on site, Custom Environmental Services utilized absorbent material on the asphalt surface, which was recovered into one (1) 55-gallon drum.  Custom Environmental Services also assisted in offloading the damaged tanker, and recovered the free product from the containment pool into one (1) 55-gallon drum.  Approximately 30 gallons of free product were released, 10 gallons to the ground surface asphalt and soil along the road shoulder, and 20 gallons contained to the containment pool beneath tanker.  Custom Environmental Services placed sorbent boom downgradient from the incident site, as a precautionary measure, pending applicable permits and favorable weather conditions, for return to site to excavate impacted soil along the road shoulder.  There were no injuries or exposures reported as a result of the release.

column168: On 1/24/11 at 16:04 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Greencastle, IN yard discovered LTCX 1615, a loaded tank car of Argon, Refrigerated Liquid, venting from the vent tube on the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Praxair Inc., was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2011-01-24-00114. Bill Baker, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene and found the car to be venting thru the vent tube due to icing on the regulating safety valve causing the valve to remain in the open position. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Tim Johnson 716-536-5354. The shipper's, Praxair Inc., technician, Joe McCort 314-422-9948, responded to the scene and warmed the regulating safety valve and thawed the plumbing in the valve box allowing the valve to close and securing the leak. The car was released for transport.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 716  NARRI: 2 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 24
column169: No additional comments.

column168: AS TONY (THE P/T SUP) OPENED THE TRAILER TO DOOR 31, HE NOTICED A LEAKING HAZMZAT PACKAGE IN THE TRAILER.  HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS.  WHEN I ARRIVED AT THE DOOR, I USED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER-SHIELD INNER LINERS.  I CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY.  I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  ONCE THE LIQUID WAS NEUTRALIZED TO A PH BETWEEN 6-9, I USED CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT TO SOLIDIFY THE LIQUID.  I SWEPT UP ALL MATERIALS USED FOR CLEAN-UP & PLACED THEM INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY.  I THEN TOOK THE LEAKING PACKAGE, THE AFFECTED PACKAGES AND THE MATERIALS USED FOR CLEAN-UP TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  WHEN I OPENED THE PACKAGE, I DISCOVERED THAT 1 OF THE 2 GLASS BOTTLES INSIDE HAD BEEN BROKEN.

column168: While setting out the UNPX 121052 (loaded covered hopper of ammonium nitrate) in Bismarck, MO, the crew found the car had released product from one of the bottom outlet slide gates. Lane Sekavec, Manager Hazardous Materials contacted Orica USA (shipper/consignee) and made arrangements for them to respond on the morning of 1/27/2011 to secure the car and remove the spilled material.         On 1/27/2011 personnel from Orica USA responded and removed approximately 400 pounds of product from three locations in the yard.  The product was taken back to the consigneess plant and no waste remained at the location.  The release was caused by a hopper slide gate that had opened slightly. column168: Consumers Energy operates an "investment recovery center", in order to recover monies from excess materials generated by statewide operations.  On January 11th, 2011, a shipment of surplus paint cans was discovered at our Jackson Service Center.  It was intended for transport to our Investment Recovery Center.  The shipment originated at our JR Whiting Electric Generating Plant.  The paint was in 1- and 5-gallon pails, packed within a lined cardboard box and wrapped in cellophane.  Approximately 620 pounds of flammable paint was contained in the shipment.  The box was a shipment of undeclared hazardous material.  The box was not marked, labeled, or recorded on a hazardous materials shipping paper.  There was no release of hazardous material.
column169: Consumers Energy is implementing several corrective actions to prevent recurrence.  Information will be sent to allpotential clients of our Investment Recovery Center.  This information will focus on the potential for creating hazardous materials shipments, and provide resources for compliance assistance.  Consumers Energy will also conduct focused meetings with our electric generating staff responsible for internal materials transfers.  These meetings will address the recognition of hazardous materials, proper handling, company personnel designated to provide assistance, and communicate existing Company hazardous materials procedures.  Finally, we will re-emphasize a theme among our drivers to "stop the job" if hazardous materials transportation concerns are identified before, during or after shipments.

column168: Sulfuric acid was being transferred from an IBC on the truck to a customer tank using an air pump under DOTSP-12412.  The product would not transfer due to a defective valve on the customer's piping (unknown at the time).  The driver closed the valve on the IBC and then disconnected the unloading hose from the IBC.  He then attempted to clear the line using air pressure.  The air line connection was not properly connected and a small amount of sulfuric acid leaked out exposing the driver who was wearing personal protective equipment and was not injured other than a precautionary rinse under a shower.
column169: Driver was informed to only use the correct air line fitting for future deliveries. Univar is reviewing the operating procedures for this process to determine if changes are needed.

column168: Please note, Schenker, Inc. shall be named as reporting party only.            According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While in the facility Dangerous Goods Area, a leak was discovered underneath a pallet, containing thirty (30), 18.9-liter plastic drums.  The area was isolated and First Environmental Nationwide of Decatur, Georgia was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  First Environmental Nationwide performed an investigation and discovered one (1) drum.  Apparently the drum rubbed against a piece of broken plastic.  Approximately 5 ounces of free product were released onto the warehouse floor.  First Environmental Nationwide removed the leaking drum and placed into a recovery drum.  First Environmental Nationwide applied absorbent material to recover the free liquid on the impacted warehouse floor.  The cleanup materials were placed into the recovery drum, along with the leaking pail, pending disposal coordination.  No injuries or exposures were reported. The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.  On Wednesday, February 2, 2011, First Environmental Nationwide transported one drum of waste to Veolia Taylor County Landfill in Mauk, Georgia for disposal.
column169: Schenker, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: The CTMV was traveling at approximately 40 mph on Griffin Road in Rural Hall, NC. The passenger side tires dropped off the edge of the roadway. In an effort by the driver to regain control of the vehicle it rolled over on the driver side and slid 30 to 40 feet before coming to a stop. A small 1/4" fitting on the meter system was cracked as a result of the roll over discharging approximately 6 gallons of propane. The leak was immediately stopped. Wreckers were called to the scene and the vehicle was recovered. The driver was treated for minor bumps and bruises.    *Note: As a precaution, two persons were evacuated for approximately 4 hours during the vehicle recovery.

column169: Retrofitted all tank trailers in Nitric Acid service with solid Teflon gaskets.

column168: Driver was travelling north on state road 113 south of Servia, IN at 20 miles per hour. He started to cough and drifted onto the unpaved shoulder. The snow and slope of the shoulder/ditch pulled him further off of the road. The driver tried to correct and get back on the road. The truck rolled over and initial reports indicate damage was done to the manway causing leakage at the seal. The incident occurred at 1:45 am EST. The shipper was notified and local authorities were called. Once we were made aware the vessel was leaking we called Environmental Remediation Services and they departed out of Fort Wayne, IN at approximately 5 am. Upon arrival at the scene, efforts were made to prevent the spill from accessing some field drainage tiles close by. This effort was successful. The release was stopped at approximately 1 pm EST with the trailer emptied into another trailer and a vacuum truck. Excavation of the contaminated soil was done immediately after the release was stopped to limit the contamination area. The site and excavated soil were tested for contamination. The site clean-up is ongoing.
column169: Designated routing will be implemented to restrict, where possible, travel on roads without shoulders or other potential hazards that can be avoided. Also, refresher driver training was done on the rollover hazards of hauling bulk materials for all of our driving employees.

LEAK EXISTED FOR APPROXIMATEY 4 HOURS UNTIL HELLER'S PERSONNEL ARRIVED AND CLOSED MANUAL VALUES TO COMPLETELY STOP THE LEAK.  THE LEAK LASTED TWO HOURS LONGER THAN IT WOULD HAVE DUE TO EMERGENCY PERSONNELS UNWILLINGNESS TO ALLOW HELLER'S PERSONNEL INTO THE SITE TO EVALUATE THE VEHICLE AND THE LEAK.  THE CLEAN-UP WAS FURTHER HINDERED BY DEP PERSONNEL WHO APPARENTLY HAD NEVER DEALT WITH A PROPANE RELATED ACCIDENT BEFORE.

column168: An H20 Environmental technician was consolidating Nitric Acid waste into a 30 gal poly drum at a customers facility to make ready for shipment. The customer  Contracted us to perform the consolidating of 16x1-gal non-DOT shippable containers of waste. The waste was identified by the client as all being the same so no compatibility issues were In question. The material was poured into a new unused 30 gal poly drum outside the building in the parking lot (loading area). After all containers were added a reaction began to occur producing orange Nitric Acid  vapors from the drum's bung opening. The technician notified his superior and was instructed to keep any people away and not to close the drum but to wait until the reaction had stopped (assuming it would reach an equilibrium shortly). A neighboring business employee called the fire department upon viewing the orange vapors emitting from the drum. The local agencies responded and established an isolation zone. Eventually, once the reaction was complete, they made entry and transferred the remaining acid liquid into another new drum that contained  approximately 20 gallons of water. It was their idea to dilute the remaining 5-6 gallons of acid into the half full drum of water. Between 1 and 3 gallons of acid had apparently bubbled out of the drum during the Initial stages of the  exothermic reaction and spilled onto some plastic sheeting that was placed under the drum prior to the bulking activities. Thus a total of not more than 10 gallons was released to the air In the form of vapors. No fire occurred, just an exothermic reaction creating an evolution of acid vapors. No one was injured as the reaction began slowly and people were excluded from the area. There was no release to any waterway or native soil. The incident did not happen during the course of transportation and the release was not caused by any container failure. It is believed that one of the waste containers identified by the client must have contained a different material (one bottle residue was later found to be a pH of 5). The entire incident took place on the customers property prior to shipping.
column169: In the future this customer's waste (due to the potential of mismarked waste containers) will be managed by lab packing the containers Instead of consolidating. This will prevent the mixing of potentially misidentified materials. H20 Environmental employees are trained to manage spills and situations not unlike this one. H20 Environmental is a haz-mat emergency responder and we perform spill clean-up so this incident normally would have been managed by us Internally. In fact, the scene was released back to us and we performed the minor cleanup of the spilled  material around the drum. Nevada OSHA performed an inspection of H20 and found no violations. H20 did not receive any Notice of Violations from the local Health Department or EPA and no enforcement action was levied against H2O  Environmental pertaining to this Incident.

column168: On January 23,2011, a Reliable Tank Line driver was putting gasoline into a 12,000  gallon underground storage tank at Quality Mart #31 at 4709 Beryl Road, Raleigh, NC.  While the driver was putting the fuel into the tank, the overflow protection valve  malfunctioned allowing the extra fuel out from the vent line. When the driver saw the fuel release he shut the release of fuel from the truck off. He then notified the clerk on duty and his terminal manager. The clerk then called the fire department. The terminal manager then called Eastern Environmental Management (EEM). At approximately, 9:05 p_m., EEM arrived on scene and met with Raleigh Fire Department to access the spill situation. It was determined that the fuel release was contained to approximately 1000' of storm drain. Containment and a vacuum truck was positioned at the out fall of the storm drain and approximately 275 gallons of water was introduced on three different flushings to move the fuel to the location where it could be vacuumed out. Once the drain tile was flushed for the third time, absorbent boom was placed into the storm drain and at the outfall to ensure that all the fuel had been captured. The oil dry that was put out on the surface spill was swept and drummed up for proper disposal. The faulty valve was replaced. The only city agency that responded was the Raleigh Fire Department

column168: During discharge of Benzene cargo in bulk from the T/B DELAWARE SUN, the primary mechanical seal on the main cargo pump failed; allowing a liquid benzene vapor to be emitted. Said vapor became frozen upon egress due to atmospheric temperature of 22 degrees F.   Vapor cloud was immediately noticed by attending tankerman, who performed an emergency stop to all discharge operations. Duration of spill estimated as less than 60 seconds.   Area around pump, which is located forward on the barge, was segregated by caution tape, and a cleanup contractor, Clean America Inc., was called in to remove the slight iced spillage in proper PPE.
column169: Following the cleanup operation, the pump well was placed under negative pressure and the mechanical seat was replaced by the manufacturer.   The failed seal, which was less than 6-months old, was returned to the manufacturer for forensic determination of the cause of the premature failure. The results of that investigation have determined that the most probable cause of the failure was a buildup on condensation in the line which may have frozen overnight due to the extremely fridgid ambient temperatures causing a temporary over pressurization of the seal’s sealing device.

column168: The driver failed to retract the delivery hose after making a residential delivery. As he drove to the next delivery the hose was dragging behind the truck. As he backed, the right rear tire ran over the delivery hose and eventually tore it in two approximately three feet from the hose reel. The driver exited the vehicle, activated the emergency shut down as he did so he received minor burns to his hands and face. The emergency shut-off system worked as designed and stopped the flow of gas. The driver was transported to a local hospital were he was treated and released. He returned to work a few days later.

column168: ON JANUARY 10, 2011 H.O. BOUCHARD DRIVER, ROGER CLOUTIER, PREPARED TO LOAD HEAVY FUEL OIL AT THE GLOBAL OIL LOADING RACK IN CHELSEA, MA. THIS PRODUCT IS A HEATED PRODUCT THAT IS TOP-LOADED INTO A NON-SPECIFICATION CARGO TANK.  IT IS ALSO WORTH NOTING THAT FALL PROTECTION IS MINIMAL AT THIS LOCATION.  THE DRIVER STANDS ON THE TOP OF THE TRAILER TO DO THE LOADING.  THE PROCEDURE IS FOR THE LOADING PIPE TO BE CHAINED TO THE TOP OF THE TRAILER TO PROTECT AGAINST SURGES IN THE LOADING PIPE THAT MAY OCCUR FROM OVERHEATED AIR OR STEAM THAT MAY BE IN THE STREAM OF OIL.  THIS PROBLEM IS OFTEN MADE WORSE WITH STEAM-TRACED OIL LINES THAT HAVE BEEN HEATING ALL WEEKEND.  IT APPEARS THAT THIS WAS THE FIRST LOAD LOADED FROM THAT RACK ON THIS MONDAY MORNING.  MR. CLOUTIER HAD INSERTED AND SECURED THE LOADING PIPE, OPENED THE PRODUCT VALVE AND STARTED THE PUMP.  THAT IS ABOUT ALL HE REMEMBERS.  HE WAS FOUND ON THE GROUND WITH THE LOADING PIPE OUT OF THE TRAILER.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF OIL WAS ALSO ON THE TRAILER AND THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER HAD SERIOUS INJURIES FROM THE FALL, NOT BECAUSE OF ANY CONTACT WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (FUEL OIL).  THE TRACTOR OR TRAILER DID NOT FAIL.  THE CARGO TANK DID NOT FAIL.  THE LOADING MACHINERY DID NOT FAIL.  IT APPEARS THAT THERE MUST HAVE BEEN FORCES THAT ACTED TO BLOW THE PIPE OUT OF THE TRAILER.  THIS CAUSED THE DRIVER TO BE KNOCKED FROM THE TRAILER TO THE GROUND.  THIS CAN HAPPEN BECAUSE OF PUMPS STARTING AND STOPPING RAPIDLY, OR STEAM OR AIR THAT HAS BEEN HEATED, PRESSURIZED AND BLOWS OUT THE DISCHARGE PIPE.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DID NOT CAUSE THE INCIDENT.  THE CARGO TANK DID NOT CAUSE THE INCIDENT. THE DRIVER FALLING IS THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: THE SOLUTION IS TO MODERNIZE THE LOADING RACKS TO PROVIDE FALL PROTECTION TO THOSE WHO ARE LOADING.

column168: ON JANUARY 7, 2011 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:15 P.M., DPNR INSPECTOR KENT E. BERNIER, JR. ENVINOMENTAL SPECIALIST, WATER POLLUTION CONTROL PROGRAM; OFFICER EVANS JACKSON, ENVIRONMENTAL ENFORCEMENT; PUBLIC WORKS, VITEMA, VIPA, AND VI FIRE, RESPONDED TO A BOYNES TRUCKING SYSTEM TANKER TRUCK OPERATED BY MR. FRANCIS SHANDALE. MR. SHANDALE WAS REMOVING THE FUEL TANKER FROM THE M/V BRIGADIER WITH A TOTAL CAPACITY OF 9,500 GALLONS OF FUEL.  AS THE FUEL TANKER DEPARTED FROM THE BARGE, THE TANKER RECEIVED A 5 INCH PUNCTURE TO THE LOWER RIGHT OF THE FIRST COMPARTMENT.  THAT FUEL COMPARTMENT CONSISTS OF 3000 GALLONS OF PREMIUM GASOLINE FUEL.  MR. SHANDALE PARKED THE TANKER ON THE RAMP, AND TRIED TO CLOG THE PUNCTURED HOLE IN THE TANKER, BUT WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE LEAK AND ABOUT 10 GALLONS OF FUEL WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANKER AND ENTERED INTO THE WATER OF ENIGHED POND.  THE V.I. FIRE SERVICE'S ZULU COMPANY RESPONDED ALONG WITH THE V.I. POLICE DEPARTMENT, WHICH BLOCKED OFF ROUTE 102 FROM THE V.I. WATER AND POWER AUTHORITY'S TREATMENT PLANT TO THE TENNIS COURT AT CRUZ BAY.  AFTER THE AREA WAS SECURED, MR. SHANDALE MOVED THE TANKER TO THE ENIGHED POND TRAILER PARKING AREA.  MR. DALE OF PUBLIC WORKS CREATED A SOIL BERM AROUND THE TANKER TO PREVENT THE GASOLINE FROM SPREADING.  A CALL WAS MADE TO LOVECO PETROLEUM, BY JAMES BOYNES TO HAVE THEM REMOVE THE REMAINING FUEL FROM THE PUNCTURED COMPARTMENT. LOVECO PETROLEUM REMOVED 2200 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AND DELIVERED IT TO EC GAS STATION.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT 790 GALLONS OF GASOLINE IMPACTED THE SOIL.  AFTER THE SITE WAS SECURED, AND ALL THE FUEL WAS CONTAINED THE TANKER WAS THEN ESCORTED BY VIPD AND VI FIRE TO EC GAS STATION, TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING FUEL FROM THE TANKER.  THE TANKER WAS THEN PUT BACK ON THE M/V BRIGADIER AND SENT BACK TO BOYNE'S TRUCKING FACILITY IN ST. THOMAS.

column168: ON JANUARY 15, 2011 AT APPROXIMATELY 16:44 HOURS, A SEMI TRACTOR TRANSPORTING A CARGO TANK (MC331) CONTAINING 9,000 GALLOONS OF LPG BUTANE (UN1075) WAS INVOLVED IN A ONE VEHICLE TRAFFIC ACCIDENT. THE SEMI WAS SOUTHBOUND ON COLO. 85. IT TRAVELED ACROSS THE NORTHBOUND LANES OF COLO. 85 AND ROLLED 1/4 TIME ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE INTO AN IRRIGATION CANAL OFF THE EAST SIDE OF COLO. 85. THE IRRIGATION CANAL WAS FILLED WITH APPROXIMATELY 3 FEET OF WATER. THE ROLLOVER DAMAGED UNDER PIPING AND VALVES ON THE CARGO TANK. THE CARGO TANK WAS LEAKING BUTANE FROM THE DAMAGED AREA. AT APPOXIMATELY 16:48 HOURS, CSP DISPATCH NOTIFIED ME OF THE INCIDENT. DISPATCH INFORMED THAT TANKER WAS ROLLED OVER AND LEAKING FLAMMABLE LIQUID WITH A PARTY TRAPPED UNDER THE TRUCK.    I ARRIVED ON-SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 17:37 HOURS. AT THE TIME OF MY ARRIVAL THE NORTHBOUND AND SOUTHBOUND LANES OF COLO. 85 WERE CLOSED AND THERE WAS A SLIGHT BREEZE TO THE NORTH. FORT LUPTON FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS APPLYING A FOG LINE ON THE LEAKING AREAS OF THE CARGO TANK AND HAD JUST FINISHED EXTRICATING THE DRIVER FROM THE VEHICLE. THE WATER FROM THE FOG LINE HELPED FORM ICE OVER THE LEAKING AREAS SLOWING THE RELEASE RATE OF THE PRODUCT. I ATTEMPTED TO CLOSE THE INTERNAL VALVES WITH THE EMERGENCY SHUTOFF WHICH HAD NO EFFECT ON THE LEAK. AT THIS TIME, MY PARTNER MARTY SMITH ARRIVED ON-SCENE. WE DETERMINED THAT BUTANE HAS A BOILING POINT OF 31 F, A LEL OF 1.6% AND A UEL OF 8.4% AND ITS VAPORS ARE HEAVIER THAN AIR. THE AIR TEMPERATURE WAS COLD ENOUGH FOR THE BUTANE TO STAY MOSTLY IN A LIQUID STATE. READINGS FROM THE 5 GAS MONITOR READ NORMAL OUTSIDE OF THE IRRIGATION CANAL. WE DECIDED TO OPEN UP THE SOUTHBOUND LANES OF COLO. 85 WHILE LEAVING THE NORTHBOUND LANES CLOSED. GREG BERKHEIMER WITH CDOT SUPERVISED THE HIGHWAY CLOSURE. COLORADO STATE PATROL TROPPERS MAINTAINED A SAFE AREA SURROUNDING THE INCIDENT SITE BY DENYIMG ENTRY TO PEOPLE WHO WERE NOT A PART OF THE INCIDENT MITIGATION. RENEWABLE FIBER IS OWNER OF THE PROPERTY ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE INCIDENT CITE. THEY ALLOWED RESCUE AND HAZMAT CREWS ACCESS ONTO  THEIR PROPERTY BECAUSE IT WAS SAFER FOR THE RESCUE CREWS AND HAZMAT MITIGATION TEAMS TO OPERATE ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE INCIDENT. APPOXIMATELY 150FT OF THEIR 65 FOOT FENCING WAS REMOVED TO ACCESS THE INCIDENT FROM THEIR PROPERTY.    MONITORING INSIDE THE CANAL READ 0 LEL AND THE HIGHEST VOC READING OF 9. ED FERGUSON, AN EMPLOYEE OF AMERIGAS AND A SPECIALIST WITH BUTANE AND MC331 CARGO TANKS ARRIVED ON-SCENE AND ASSISTED US WITH KNOWLEDGE OF THE PRODUCT AND THE INTERNAL PIPING OF THE CARGO TANK. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT IT WAS SAFE TO MAKE AN OFFLOAD CONNECTION AT THE REAR OF THE CARGO TANK TO OFFLOAD AS MUCH BUTANE AS POSSIBLE WITHOUT MOVING THE CARGO TANK. FORT LUPTON FIRE APPLIED A FOG LINE ACROSS THE CANAL BEFORE EACH ENTRY INTO THE IRRIGATION CANAL TO DISPLACE ANY BUILDUP OF VAPORS THAT MAY HAVE ACCUMULATED BETWEEN ENTRIES. FORT LUPTON FIRE PROVIDED A CHARGED HOSE FOR FIRE PROTECTION AND EMERGENCY DE

Our operations manager suggested to the township manager that the intersection could be widened to prevent any reoccurence due to the fact that another truck overturned at the same intersection only days later.   Weather also played a factor in that the roads were icey.

column168: On January 10, 2011 a delivery driver employee was making a propane gas delivery to the underground ASME propane storage tank located at the Mangrove Cafe at 878 5th Ave S., Naples, Florida.  The tank is located underground in the cafe's parking lot located at the rear of the business.  The driver attached the hose-end fill nozzle to the tank's fill valve and initiated the process of transferring propane into the tank.  The ACME threaded portion of the tank's fill valve, which was the connection point to the hose-end fill nozzle, tore from the body of the fill valve.  As a result, we believe approximately 20 gallons of propane were released.  The resulting propane vapor cloud came in contact with an unknown source of ignition, thus resulting in an explosion and fire.       The incident is under investigation by the Naples Fire Department, the Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services (LP Gas Bureau) and the Florida Fire Marshal.  Notwithstanding the ongoing investigations, the specific cause of the failure of the fill valve on the ASME storage tank is unknown.  The only known witnesses to the incident are the delivery driver employee and Donald Kingston, an employee/contractor of a restaurant/bar service company who was present working on the beer tap lines at the restaurant and had parked his Nissan automobile within several feet of the hose-end nozzle assembly, and who advised the fire investigators to having seen "fog" coming from the area of the nozzle.  Reporting party does not believe Mr. Kingston has provided any information suggesting the cause of the failure of the hose-end nozzle-fill valve connection.  Reporting party's employee has been unable to provide a written or verbal statement concerning the cause of the failure of the hose-end nozzle-fill valve connection due to the extent of his injuries.
column169: This incident remains under investigation by the authorities identified in Part VI above, as well as by OSHA.
